{"parse":{"title":"Private benefits of control","pageid":21591658,"revid":733588327,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Private benefits of control</b> is a technical term used by <a href=\"/wiki/Corporate_law\" title=\"Corporate law\">corporate lawyers</a> and economists. It refers to the economic gain from exerting influence on a company by large shareholders at the expense of small shareholders.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Types\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Types</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Protection\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Protection</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Notes\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Notes</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Types\">Types</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Private_benefits_of_control&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Types\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>There are two different types of private benefits of control from company value perspective: Benefits which reduce the value of company and which do not so. An example was given by Barclay and Holderness, in comparison to benefits that accrue to all shareholders by raising the productivity of the company.\n</p>\n<table class=\"cquote pullquote\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"margin:auto; border-collapse: collapse; border: none; background-color: transparent; width: auto;\">\n<tbody><tr>\n<td style=\"width: 20px; vertical-align: top; border: none; color: #B2B7F2; font-size: 40px; font-family: &#39;Times New Roman&#39;, Times, serif; font-weight: bold; line-height: .6em; text-align: left; padding: 10px 10px;\">\u201c\n</td>\n<td style=\"vertical-align: top; border: none; padding: 4px 10px;\">The private benefits can be pecuniary, including higher salaries for individual blockholders or below-market transfer prices for corporate blockholders. For example, T. Boone Pickens alleges that Koito, a Japanese auto part maker, has for many years been subsidizing sales to a large shareholder, the <a href=\"/wiki/Toyota\" title=\"Toyota\">Toyota</a> Car Group. Mr. Pickens recently bought a large block of stock in Koito and demanded board representation, in part to stop the private benefits that allegedly have been flowing to Toyota. Private benefits need not come from the firm\u2019s cash flows, however. For example, there may be nonpecuniary control amenities for individual blockholders [Demsetz and Lehn (1985)] or <a href=\"/wiki/Synergies\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Synergies\">synergies</a> in production for corporate blockholders [Bradley (1980)].<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</td>\n<td style=\"width: 20px; vertical-align: bottom; border: none; color: #B2B7F2; font-size: 40px; font-family: &#39;Times New Roman&#39;, Times, serif; font-weight: bold; line-height: .6em; text-align: right; padding: 10px 10px;\">\u201d\n</td></tr>\n\n</tbody></table>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Protection\">Protection</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Private_benefits_of_control&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Protection\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>In order to prevent the impact on the small shareholders from the realization of these benefits of large shareholders, there is usually a <a href=\"/wiki/Mandatory_Offer\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Mandatory Offer\">Mandatory Offer</a> policy in transaction area for protection of the small shareholders from kinds of value-destroying transactions.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Private_benefits_of_control&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Corporate_governance\" title=\"Corporate governance\">Corporate governance</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Control_premium\" title=\"Control premium\">Control premium</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Mandatory_Offer\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Mandatory Offer\">Mandatory Offer</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notes\">Notes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Private_benefits_of_control&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Notes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist columns references-column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">MJ Barclay and CG Holderness, 'Private Benefits of Control in Public Corporations' (1989) 25 Journal of Financial Economics 371, 374. The authors go on to argue these benefits could be measured by differences in stock prices: \" Our block trades are typically negotiated at arm\u2019s length, and the trading parties presumably forecast rationally the effect of their trade on the stock\u2019s exchange price. Thus, any private benefits will be reflected in the difference between the block-trade price and the post-announcement exchange price.\"</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Private_benefits_of_control&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li>MJ Barclay and CG Holderness, 'Private Benefits of Control in Public Corporations' (1989) 25 Journal of Financial Economics 371</li></ul>\n<p><br />\n</p>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:ThreeCoins.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Stub icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/29/ThreeCoins.svg/40px-ThreeCoins.svg.png\" width=\"40\" height=\"23\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/29/ThreeCoins.svg/60px-ThreeCoins.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/29/ThreeCoins.svg/80px-ThreeCoins.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"350\" data-file-height=\"200\" /></a></td><td><i>This <a href=\"/wiki/Economics\" title=\"Economics\">economics</a>-related article is a <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Stub\" title=\"Wikipedia:Stub\">stub</a>. You can help Wikipedia by <a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Private_benefits_of_control&amp;action=edit\">expanding it</a>.</i><div class=\"plainlinks hlist navbar mini\" style=\"position: absolute; right: 15px; display: none;\"><ul><li class=\"nv-view\"><a href=\"/wiki/Template:Econ-stub\" t